ce:section.ce:para:
Table 7 displays the calculation time for all mesh counts and the three numbers of elements (
N el
) in the discretised particles together with the battery potential and core temperature standard deviations. By means of a CPU (Intel® Xeron® Gold 6226R, 2.90GHz) and RAM of 64 GB, each computation lasts between 16 and 262 s, according to the number of mesh. This is 1356 % increase in comparison with the lumped model computation time (i.e. maximum 18 s in [22]). As was expected, the single particle model does not offer a similar generalisation as in the lumped semi-empirical model [22] which is similar to the existing studies of physics-based models in the literature ([17,23]). In fact, as soon as the charge rates in the computations varied, different negative electrode diffusion coefficient values were chosen, which is identical to a calibrated DFN model by Chen et al. [17] which used same commercial battery. However, it is noteworthy that for all the C-rates the rest of input parameters are set to 1C discharge experimental data in [17], therefore, the single particle model shows an acceptable level of generalisation.
